title: Electoral Assistance in Afghanistan
description: Funding under this initiative provides electoral support in Afghanistan, specifically to: implement the voter registration process; undertake voter education and public outreach activities; and strengthen the capacity of the independent elections Commission in support of greater transparency and accountability process for the 2010 Afghanistan Parliamentary Election. By contributing to both the formal and informal institutions of the electoral process, Australia is working with the Government of Afghanistan to ensure free and fair elections take place as well as working with civil society to strengthen voice and empower social groups (especially women) to demand better services from the government and mobilise efforts against corruption. The total value of this initiative is $10.1 million over 3 years, starting 2008-09.

title: Pacific Partnership with AEC
description: The Pacific Partnership with Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) aims to enhance the capacity of electoral administrators and improve the governance and sustainability of electoral management bodies through training, development of strategic plans, upgrading of the Generic Voter Registration System database roll in Vanuatu and the establishment of a Pacific Islands, Australia and New Zealand Electoral Administrators (PIANZEA) website to provide members with a means to communicate and capture electoral issues and events. The total value of this initiative is $2.5 million over 3 years, starting 2011-12.

title: Support to UNDP on Bangladesh National Election
description: Funding under this initiative provides support to the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) to deliver technical assistance to the Bangladesh Election Commission, specifically: online systems for results and candidate management; technical assistance to train staff on methodologies, training aids and materials; procurement of logistics including ballot boxes; and coordination of public debates for the candidates in 10 regions across the country. The total value of this initiative is $1.0 million to be expensed during the 2012-13 financial year.

title: Afghanistan Elections Assistance
description: This investment aims to provide support to Afghan parliamentary elections (held in October 2018) by providing assistance to electoral management bodies to strengthen the integrity of electoral processes, enhancing accountability of responsible actors, and implementing electoral fraud mitigation mechanisms. The total estimated value of this investment is $7.0 million, to be expensed during the 2018-19 financial year.

title: Fiji Transition to Democracy
description: The Fiji Transition to Democracy initiative aims to: support Fiji Elections Office to help conduct a national voter registration exercise as part of the introduction of electronic voter registration; support to the Constitution Commission; and support for civic education by working with the United Nations Development Program to implement a national civic education program with civil society and government. The program also supports the government's civil service reform through targeted technical assistance. The total value of this initiative is $5.6 million over 3 years, starting 2012-13.

title: AEC PIANZEA 2016-2019
description: Pacific Islands, Australia and New Zealand Electoral Administrators Network (PIANZEA) Support Program enables the AEC to enhance the capacity of electoral administration and build the capacity of electoral management bodies. Over time this will support provision of high quality electoral services, which support democratic process. The program supports a work plan covering a range of activities including training, conferences, exchanges and technical support and advice. The total value of this investment is $1.7 million over 4 years, starting May 2016.

donor_name: The Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs
title: Strengthening Citizen Election Observer Capacity in the DRC (ND)
description:
Citizen Election Observer Groups (esp. CEJP), electoral stakeholders and authorities. ▪	Objective 1: Improved Monitoring, Analysis, and Reporting. Civil society credibly monitors and reports on key emerging issues related to elections; and

▪	Objective 2: Enhanced Advocacy for Reform. Civil society implements evidence-based advocacy campaigns to contribute constructively to policy and practice reforms related to elections. Since 2010, The Carter Center’s Citizen Observation (CO) program in the DRC has been working with the Catholic Church’s Episcopal Commission for Justice and Peace (CENCO/CEJP) to strengthen their capacity to promote democratic elections in the DRC by independently conducting meaningful observation of electoral processes.  With support from the Kingdom of the Netherlands, Carter Center staff will continue working with CENCO/CEJP to strengthen their ability to identify and respond quickly and effectively to key issues and aspects of the electoral process that are vulnerable to manipulation, to gather data specifically related to those areas, and to develop strong and targeted recommendations to stakeholders to address those issues and minimize impact on the electoral process. Small sub-grants will be provided to gather targeted data and then use it to facilitate timely outreach, advocacy and follow-up activities. This will also help increase partner CSOs’ financial and grants management capacity.

donor_name: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Local Cooperation Fund (LCF) in Kenya
description:
Election observation is defined as the purposeful gathering of information regarding an electoral process and making informed judgements about the process on the basis of information collected. Over the years election observation in Kenya has largely focus
ed on Election Day processes and activities an approach that fails to take into cognizance the environment and processes prior to and after the elections. ELOG has organized itself as a comprehensive election monitoring and observation programme. Its aim i
s to promote trasparency and accountability in the lectoral processes in Kenya and the Africa Region. Taking elections as a process and not an event ELOG has identified seven key thematic issues under which thematic monitoring and observation shall be anch
ored namely: voter registration monitoring and implenetation of political parties Act and political financing advocacy on electoral law reform and constituency delimitation campaign monitoring promotion and participation of marginalized groups voter educat
ion and media monitoring. This is anticipated to set a comprehensive background and environment for actual election-day monittoring and observation which will utize the traditional observation and parallel vote tabulation methodologies for purposes of dete
rring electoral malpractices and the swift verification of the official results and the credibility of the election-day processesObjectives, to enhance stakeholder awareness on the electoral process undertake comprehensive thematic monitoring and observati
on of electora process leading to and after the 2012 elections to faciliate the stablishment and build capacity for a peace panel to undertake election day observation through fielding general observers and parallel vote tabulation observers

donor_name: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Electoral support to Mozambique 2018-2020
description:
The main focus of this project is to improve transparency credibility and inclusiveness in Mozambique's local and general elections in 2018 and 2019. The project offers training support and new tools for the election officials district judges and the civil
 society. Mozambique has faced challenges with credibility and transparency in the election process during previous elections. Turnout has been low the declaration of the final results has been delayed and the complaint-procedures have been difficult and u
nclear. In the general elections of 2019 the provincial governors will be elected by voters for the first time. This supports the decentralization of political power in Mozambique and therefore it is crucial that the elections are conducted as transparentl
y credibly and inclusively as possible. The electoral support to Mozambique will increase transparency and inclusion in the electoral process develop training and new tools for election officials and other stakeholders increase the participation of women a
nd young voters in the electoral process as well as improve the mechanisms for electoral disputes.The project aims to increase equality the fulfillment of rights of women and girls the political parties' ability to use electoral complaint-procedures and to
 increase turnout. The project is administered by the UNDP and has been planned in close cooperation with the Technical Secretariat for the Administration of Election and National Elections Committee which are the key Election Management Bodies in Mozambiq
ue.

donor_name: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: UNDP Support for the Timorese Electoral Cycle
description:
Timor-Leste?s presidential and legislative elections in 2007 were the first national post-independence elections organized by the Timorese and as such represented an important step in the consolidation of democracy in the country. The next parliamentary el
ections are to be held in July 2012. The UNDP Support to the Timorese Electoral Cycle project using an Electoral Cycle Approach supports the capacity development of the Electoral Management Bodies (EMBs) in Timor-Leste:  The Technical Secretariat for Elect
oral Administration (STAE) and the National Commission on Elections (CNE) and the political parties. Based on the lessons learned from electoral support in Timor-Leste and in view of the need to further strengthen the human and institutional capacity of th
e national electoral management bodies and political parties the project provides selected assistance in priority areas throughout the preparation and implementation of upcoming parliamentary elections. The activities are 1) advisory support for the STAE a
nd CNE including expert and technical assistance in the pre-electoral period and individual mentoring in the post-electoral period and 2) support to voter and civic education in designing and producing a comprehensive range of voter and civic education cam
paigns.  The project activities cover all the districts of Timor-Leste and the duration of the project is from July to December 2012. The Timorese Electoral Cycle project is expected to conclude in December 2012.

donor_name: Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC)
implementing_name: ONG basée dans un pays donneur
title: Support to Tanzania’s Election Cycle
description: The proposed intervention supports the Tanzanian Electoral Management Bodies (EMBs) and the media in Tanzania for the Constitutional referendum 2014 and local and general elections in 2014/2015. EMBs will be supported for institutional reforms and capacity strengthening to guarantee free and credible elections. The media will be strengthened in its role as watchdog and citizen informer to provide for impartial political reporting.

implementing_name: UNDP - UN Development Programme;UNDP - UN Development Programme
title: Post-Elections Technical Assistance to Angola
description: Angola conducted elections in August 2017. Prior to the elections, Norway supported a project aimed at capacity building in the areas of democratic awareness and electoral observation (AGO-17/0002). The current project aims to expand the post-elections technical assistance to address a wider set of challenges identified from the August elections, including within the electoral management, electoral dispute processes and mechanisms, political intolerance and access to media.

description: The programme with NEC responds to the need to continue supporting the institutional strengthening of NEC in the use of ICT in election management; capacity building for staff through BRIDGE methodology; support NEC efforts in developing and conducting voter education; strengthen the role and functions of key institutions, i.e. media, civil society organizations and political parties. title: AIP for Electoral Support 2010
description: Indonesian Electoral Systems Support Program (IESSP) aims to strengthen the management of electoral processes and democratic consolidation in Indonesia, thus fulfilling the objectives of the Australian Government, the Government of Indonesia's long term and medium term goals, and strengthening the Australia/Indonesia bilateral relationship. The total value of this initiative is $5.0 million over 3 years, starting 2009-10.

title: Direct Bilateral Assistance
description: The Direct Bilateral Assistance initiative forms part of the Development Partnership with the Caribbean, and focuses on building regional economic resilience and integration, and supporting small island states to address the threat of climate change. The funding under this initiative is used to support various activities that help to achieve the above goals, including: reconstruction of the St Jude Hospital in St Lucia; reconstruction of the Grenada Parliament House; emergency response funding to hurricane Tomas; judicial assistance to Belize; coral reef management; regional electoral assistance; and regional land registration assistance. The total value of this multi-country initiative is $10.6 million over 5 years, starting 2009-10.

title: Pacific Partnership with AEC
description: The Pacific Partnership with Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) aims to enhance the capacity of electoral administrators and improve the governance and sustainability of electoral management bodies through training, development of strategic plans, upgrading of the Generic Voter Registration System database roll in Vanuatu and the establishment of a Pacific Islands, Australia and New Zealand Electoral Administrators (PIANZEA) website to provide members with a means to communicate and capture electoral issues and events. The total value of this initiative is $2.5 million over 3 years, starting 2011-12.

title: Australia Indonesia Electoral Support Program
description: Australia Indonesia Electoral Support Program supports building a prosperous democratic and stable Indonesia. Indonesia's next election will take place in 2014 and approximately 300 sub-national local executive elections will take place between 2011 and 2013. Key objectives are to improve management of elections by electoral management bodies; and increased public engagement in the electoral process. The total value of this initiative is $22.8 million over 5 years, starting 2010-11.

title: Myanmar-Australia Partnership for Reform
description: The Myanmar-Australia Partnership for Reform aims to help strengthen democratic institutions, promote human rights and advance the rule of law, including supporting a free and fair election in 2015. The Partnership has three pillars targeting the development of the institutions central to Myanmar succeeding in reform and improved governance. Pillar 1: Institutions for effective delivery of public services, including support to strengthen public expenditure management, and to deliver a quality census. Pillar 2: institutions for conflict resolution and peace-building, including investing in community peace-building efforts and assistance that demonstrates the dividend from conflict resolution. Pillar 3: Institutions for an accountable and responsive state, including support to improve resource management and revenue transparency, elections and human rights. The total value of this initiative is $38.0 million over 3 years, starting 2012-13.

title: Independent Monitoring and Evaluation Services for DDiN2
description: This activity (Independent Monitoring and Evaluation Services for DDiN2) is a component of Deepening Democracy in Nigeria 2 (DDIN2) reported by DFID, with a funding type of 'Procurement of Services' and a budget of £119,691. This component benefits Nigeria, and works in the following sector(s): Public sector policy and administrative management, Democratic participation and civil society, Elections, Media and free flow of information, Human rights, Women's equality organisations and institutions. , with the following implementing partners: Coffey International Development. title: Civil Society and Governance Support
description: The goal of the project is to support the governance capacities of a select group of government, civil society and private sector institutions in an effort to ensure a responsible, equitable state that respects the rights of its citizens. Areas of support include: judicial administration, management of public funds, the electoral process, democratic development and ensuring basic human rights are upheld in Cameroon. As a result of this project the men and women of Cameroon are expected to be better informed as to their individual rights, to be more involved in their communities and able to actively improve their quality of life.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement
title: Deepening Democracy in Tanzania Program
description: The Deepening Democracy in Tanzania Program (DDTP) supports four broad strategic areas of democracy in Tanzania, namely: 1) the Facilitation and implementation of the African Peer Review Mechanism; 2) the elections management bodies and the electoral process; 3) civic education; and 4) good and accountable governance.   These broad strategic areas have been selected following extensive consultations with government, civil society and development partners. The expected results of the DDTP are to secure and expand democratic achievements to date by strengthening the capacity of democratic institutions, including Parliament, the House of Representatives, the election management bodies of Tanzania and Zanzibar, civil society, the media, and political parties through training, technical assistance and relevant activities.

implementing_name: Gouvernement du Mali - Ministère de l'Administration territoriale et des Collectivités locales
title: Presidential and Legislative Elections 2007
description: The main objective of the project is to strengthen the democratization process in Mali by holding credible, transparent, fair, and equitable presidential and legislative elections. The purpose of the project is to build the Government of Mali’s capacities and means to hold widely participatory, transparent, and credible elections.   The project is organized around the following components and activities: contribution to the election support pooled fund established by the Ministry of Territorial Administration and Local Communities (MATCL) to channel partner funds; election training, including training of staff responsible for steering, managing and controlling the election process, as well as polling station personnel; deployment of steering, management, and control mechanisms; regulated and equitable media coverage; and the management and control of security measures.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement
title: 2010 Electoral Support Program
description: The 2010 Electoral Support Program's main goal is to provide technical and logistical support to Tanzania’s Elections Management Bodies, the National Electoral Commission, and the Zanzibar Electoral Commission for ensuring the conduct of free, fair and credible elections, for engaging political parties, media and civil society, as well as providing support and training to government institutions tasked with maintaining public safety and security before, during and after the voting. The latter is crucial to Zanzibar, where the very close competition between the two major parties has often contributed to insecurity and violent incidents around election time.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement - Zambie
title: Strengthening Electoral Processes in Zambia
description: The project aims to enhance effectiveness of the Electoral Commission of Zambia to conduct transparent and fair elections. More specifically, it aims to: enhance accuracy of the voter register; increase capacity of the National Voter Education Committee to coordinate, plan and implement continuous voter education; strengthen participation by women as candidates and strengthen organizational capacity of civil society organisations working in the area of women's political rights in Zambia; strengthen capacity of the Electoral Commission of Zambia to engage the media; and revise the legislative framework and code of conduct to ensure a viable and fair means of redress in the event of electoral malpractices.

title: Central Governance Transition Project
description: This project is a follow up phase to the successful Central Governance project which ended in June 2008. The goal of this project is to continue to enhance the Government of Ghana's policy management process. The project strengthens the foundations of Ghana's executive decision-making system through the application of products, procedures and processes developed in the previous phase of the Central Governance project. It also builds the capacity of the Ghanaian management to implement reforms. The Government of Ghana asked CIDA to assist with the development of its executive decision-making system, which is a central element of its overall public sector reforms.   The project contributes to the increased knowledge and application of skills of policy development and decision-making requirements of staff in key central Ministries and Departments (including Ministries of Finance and Economic Planning, Food and Agriculture, Local Government and Rural Development, Health, Education and Women and Children's Affairs) as well as the Office of the President. The use of standard formats and tracking of Cabinet documents has continued successfully, demonstrating integration and usefulness of the new processes into the Government's practices. The transition from one government to another following the December 2008 elections has gone well; handover notes prepared by each Ministry and Department by outgoing Ministers for those incoming made an important contribution to a smooth transition.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement
title: ELECT - Voter Registration
description: This project helped Afghanistan’s Independent Elections Commission (IEC) to conduct voter registration in preparation for the 2009 presidential and provincial council elections and the 2010 parliamentary elections. The project is supporting one component of the United Nations Development Programme’s Enhancing Legal and Electoral Capacity for Tomorrow project (UNDP-ELECT).    The voter registration component strengthened the IEC’s ability to design and implement a sustainable national voter registration system, to inform the Afghan public about voter registration, and to engage the Afghan public in electoral processes. It included the creation of a data centre to process the voter information collected; training for IEC personnel; the provision of technical assistance to IEC; public outreach activities; external relations activities, media conferences, and stakeholder forums; payment of salaries for IEC temporary staff; the procurement of equipment, commodities, and facilities; and transportation of voter registration materials and personnel.   This project represents CIDA’s contribution to the voter registration component of the UNDP-ELECT project. CIDA’s total contribution to UNDP-ELECT is $25 million.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement
title: Enhancing Legal and Electoral Capacity for Tomorrow (UNDP-ELECT)
description: The purpose of the United Nations Development Programme’s Enhancing Legal and Electoral Capacity for Tomorrow project (UNDP-ELECT) is to support the 2009 presidential and provincial council elections and the 2010 parliamentary elections in Afghanistan. By working directly with the Independent Election Commission (IEC) of Afghanistan, the Electoral Complaints Commission (ECC), and Electoral Media Commission, UNDP-ELECT enables Afghan officials to provide leadership in these elections in areas such as registering voters, recruiting and training election officials, producing and transporting election materials, and verifying election results.   This contribution represents CIDA’s support for UNDP-ELECT activities other than voter registration. The project UNDP-ELECT - Voter Registration represents CIDA’s contribution to the voter registration component of UNDP-ELECT. CIDA’s total contribution to UNDP-ELECT is $25 million.

title: Enhancing Legal and Electoral Capacity for Tomorrow (UNDP-ELECT)
description: The purpose of the United Nations Development Programme’s Enhancing Legal and Electoral Capacity for Tomorrow project (UNDP-ELECT) is to support the 2009 presidential and provincial council elections and the 2010 parliamentary elections in Afghanistan. By working directly with the Independent Election Commission (IEC) of Afghanistan, the Electoral Complaints Commission (ECC), and Electoral Media Commission, UNDP-ELECT enables Afghan officials to provide leadership in these elections in areas such as registering voters, recruiting and training election officials, producing and transporting election materials, and verifying election results.   This contribution represents CIDA’s support for UNDP-ELECT activities other than voter registration. The project UNDP-ELECT - Voter Registration represents CIDA’s contribution to the voter registration component of UNDP-ELECT. CIDA’s total contribution to UNDP-ELECT is $25 million.

implementing_name: USAID - United States Agency for International Development
title: Support to the Municipal and Regional Electoral Process in Tunisia
description: The goal of this project is to improve the integrity of and support the municipal and regional electoral process in Tunisia scheduled for May 2018. The project provides tailored approaches to rural areas with higher illiteracy rates to ensure women have equal opportunities to participate in the electoral process.  Project activities include: (1) providing training to targeted civil society organizations to strengthen their organizational capacity to observe municipal elections throughout the country, and ensure gender equity among observers; (2) providing training to 300 new women ambassadors so they are equipped with outreach tools to interact face-to-face with registered women and persuade them to vote; and (3) civic educators conduct targeted civic and voter education campaigns for rural illiterate women, youth and marginalized groups, through radio programming, videos or coffee talks.  Through GAC’s support, this project contributes to a USAID project by expanding current outreach activities for illiterate rural women in both geographic coverage and scope reaching up to 7.6 million radio listeners and viewers.

title: Support of Women's Capacity to Mediate Electoral Conflicts in DRC
description: The project is designed to contribute to peace consolidation in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) by getting women significantly involved in a peaceful electoral process. The project is helping to improve women’s participation in managing electoral conflicts and in promoting civic education in 10 provinces. Project activities include the following: (1) building the capacity of 45 women leaders in electoral conflict mediation and management; (2) organizing three capacity-building workshops for 45 women candidates or potential candidates on developing communication strategies in an election period, the various legal instruments protecting women, and advocacy; (3) organizing 16 advocacy missions about appointing women and girls to decision-making positions; (4) subsidizing 16 women’s organizations so they can implement projects pertaining to outreach, women’s participation in the electoral process, preventing and managing electoral conflicts, electoral observation and monitoring the status of women; and (5) organizing three capacity-building sessions on civic education and electoral observation for 30 women and girl leaders.

donor_name: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: Electoral support to Mozambique 2018-2020
description:
The main focus of this project is to improve transparency credibility and inclusiveness in Mozambique's local and general elections in 2018 and 2019. The project offers training support and new tools for the election officials district judges and the civil
 society. Mozambique has faced challenges with credibility and transparency in the election process during previous elections. Turnout has been low the declaration of the final results has been delayed and the complaint-procedures have been difficult and u
nclear. In the general elections of 2019 the provincial governors will be elected by voters for the first time. This supports the decentralization of political power in Mozambique and therefore it is crucial that the elections are conducted as transparentl
y credibly and inclusively as possible. The electoral support to Mozambique will increase transparency and inclusion in the electoral process develop training and new tools for election officials and other stakeholders increase the participation of women a
nd young voters in the electoral process as well as improve the mechanisms for electoral disputes.The project aims to increase equality the fulfillment of rights of women and girls the political parties' ability to use electoral complaint-procedures and to
 increase turnout. The project is administered by the UNDP and has been planned in close cooperation with the Technical Secretariat for the Administration of Election and National Elections Committee which are the key Election Management Bodies in Mozambiq
ue.

title: Electoral Transition Support - Building capacity of Domestic Observation & Women's Participation
description: The objective of the Electoral Transition Support envelope of $19.5 million is to contribute to national efforts to strengthen democracy and good governance in Haiti. It supports the organization of free, transparent, and fair elections during electoral processes. It includes technical and material support to the Electoral Council and other key national electoral bodies, and a responsive fund that supports local electoral observation and public awareness programs that encourage Haitians to participate in elections.  There are several components and various implementing partners of this initiative. Some activities are implemented by civil society organizations in Haiti, and others offer technical support such as that provided by Elections Canada to Haitian authorities for the organization and management of electoral processes. For the elections in 2015, one component provides support through the National Democratic Institute to build capacity for local electoral observation and for women's political participation.

It includes technical and material support to the Electoral Council and other key national electoral bodies, and a responsive fund that supports local electoral observation and public awareness programs that encourage Haitians to participate in elections.  There are several components and various implementing partners of this initiative. Some activities are implemented by civil society organizations in Haiti, and others offer technical support such as that provided by Elections Canada to Haitian authorities for the organization and management of electoral processes. For the elections in 2015, one component provides support through the National Democratic Institute to build capacity for local electoral observation and for women's political participation.

implementing_name: PNUD - Programme des Nations Unies pour le développement
title: Strengthening the Electoral Process and Democracy in Tanzania
description: This project aims to strengthen democratic electoral processes in the lead-up to the constitutional referendum (2014) and the general elections (2015). The project aims to increase the effectiveness of election management bodies and other key democratic institutions, increase civic participation and engagement in political and electoral processes, and prevent election-related conflict. Strengthened electoral processes lead to an enhanced democratic environment, economic growth, and stability in Tanzania.  Some project activities include: (i) supporting the National Electoral Commission in updating election regulations and guidelines; (ii) supporting dialogue between the electoral management bodies, civil society organizations, media and political parties to improve the legal and institutional framework for democratic and inclusive elections in Tanzania; (iii) supporting skills and capacity development for women, youth and people with disabilities as potential candidates and party leaders; (iv) promoting public awareness on gender equality and women's empowerment through community dialogue and voter education; and (v) providing human rights and gender awareness training for the police.

implementing_name: IFES - International Foundation for Electoral Systems
title: Pakistan Electoral System Support
description: This project aims to strengthen the management ability of the Election Commission of Pakistan and increase the participation of voters in Pakistan's political system. More specifically, it seeks to improve the credibility of the country’s election system and increase voter registration and turnout. The project supports the Election Commission's five-year strategic plan by providing technical expertise and training on all aspects of election management. It focuses on engaging youth and promoting the rights of women and minorities to ensure their representation in the democratic process.  The project is implemented by the International Foundation for Electoral Systems in cooperation with local civil society organizations.

implementing_name: IFES - International Foundation for Electoral Systems
title: Kenya Electoral System Support
description: This initiative seeks to reduce the barriers that prevented the participation of 45.7% of the eligible voting population in the 2007 elections by implementing a civic and voter education program. The project also focuses on improving voter registration and identification systems. The goal is to ensure the accuracy, credibility and representativeness of the voters' roll so that previously disadvantaged groups, such as women and youth, are included.  Some project activities include: (i) conducting focus groups and stakeholder consultations in five pilot constituencies to collect information on low voter turnout, particularly among women and youth; (ii) implementing a civic and voter education program in up to five pilot constituencies, with help from Elections Canada, and scaling the program up to the national level; (iii) working with Kenya’s Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC) and the National Registration Bureau (NRB) to establish a protocol for sharing national citizen registration and voter registration data between the two organizations to capture the necessary voter registration information; and (iv) supporting Kenya’s IEBC to develop and implement a strategy for the sustainable, reliable and credible use of election technology, in particular, biometric voter registration kits.

implementing_name: IFES - International Foundation for Electoral Systems
title: Advancing Democracy through a Strong and Inclusive Electoral Process
description: The project aims to increase the credibility and effectiveness of elections in Indonesia ahead of the next national elections in 2019, benefitting up to 186 million registered voters. It seeks to strengthen the legal framework and the ability of Indonesia election authorities to administer future elections, reduce election-related violence and increase the participation of women, youth and marginalized groups in the electoral process. The project integrates lessons learned from the 2014 national elections into the next election cycle (2014–2019), most importantly into the new legislature’s deliberations on the fundamental electoral legal framework reform.  Project activities are implemented countrywide with a special focus on areas of greatest risk for contested or violent elections, such as Aceh and Eastern Indonesia. Project activities include: (1) providing technical assistance to legislators and civil society on how to prepare and support reforms to elections laws; (2) training women leaders and conducting advocacy campaigns to increase the number of women in the election commission and in political representation; (3) training election management personnel to improve access for voters with disabilities; (4) assisting the election commission with upgrades to key systems and databases such as the voter registration list; (5) developing voter education campaigns and social media tools to inform the electorate (in particular youth, women and marginalized groups) about voting rights, the process and the importance of participation.
